Now in Argentina, people are disappearing.
In the world, now right now, thousands of people disappear.
Some are missing who are alive, as a result of child trafficking, baby theft, human trafficking, illegal adoptions.
Others are missing who have died: kidnappings, wars, narco-violence, terrorist attacks, natural accidents and others not so natural.
You need to return your identity, rewrite your first and last name.
Because we all have an identity, we have an individuality, an identity of individual, affective, family, cultural, group, country, but we also have a genetic identity.
It is written in our genes our identity.
Our genome, the human genome, is made up of four letters that are repeated 3000 million times.
Amazing!
But we're almost the same.
Almost the same!
To be exact, our genome is 99.9% identical among us.
Only 0.1% of our genome allows us to distinguish or identify ourselves.
Now, 0.1% of 3000 million letters is no less than three million letters and that is a number.
You can write some books with three million letters.
And that is what it is, of, using the letters of our genome, to rewrite the letters of the name and surname of those who lost their identity.
How do we do it?
Using genetics, comparing.
To identify is necessarily to compare.
To compare a father and a son, to know if they are linked in that kinship, I have to compare them.
And know that there is a proportion of those letters that they have in common according to that kinship.
In the 80’s, I was working in the Hospital de Clínicas, on the genetics of transplants, looking for maximum genetic compatibility between donors and organ recipients to avoid graft rejection.
And you'll wonder, and what does that have to do with identity?
It has to see and a lot.
And how much!
Because our body, our immune system, is deeply xenophobic.
It self-recognizes itself as such and tolerates and rejects all the strange.
And that's why we reject a virus, a bacterium, how much more are we going to reject an entire organ.
That’s why we were looking for those compatibility, to avoid those rejections.
But also those genes allowed us, precisely because we did it between related relatives, analyze and establish kinship bonds.
We had a problem in the 80’s: we needed living cells from the two people we were going to compare, we couldn’t analyze a bone.
That was a stumbling block.
