The book did not awaken in me the vocation for medicine or chemistry, but my passion for history.
And, as a frequent traveler to the past, I wanted to tell you something about the pandemics that hit humanity.
We could talk about the fierce anger of the second half of the 19th century, or the smallpox that cost so much to dominate.
But there are two pandemics that were very marked by their fatal consequences.
In the 14th century, the Black Death, caused by a lice that moved in rats.
It began in Asia and from there it passed to Venice, the most cosmopolitan port of its time.
That's how he got into Europe.
The death was between 25 and 50 million.
From every four Europeans to one was taken by the plague.
The numbers in Asia were quite similar.
Closer in time, in the 20th century, the century of flus, we had in 1918 the Spanish flu.
Spanish flu that began in the U.S. with American soldiers preparing to go to the end of the First World War and that infected the populations of the ports of France where they embarked.
From there it spread all over the continent.
It started in the U.S. and came to Europe for France.
Why do we call it the Spanish flu?
Well, that was a "fake news."
The government and the press of Spain decided to face evil by putting statistics on the surface.
For that sinceration of the data and the numbers they ended up being pointed out as responsible for something that did not correspond to them.
At that time one in five infected died.
Look, in World War I, between 10 and 30 million people died.
Universal flu killed 50 million.
The world population declined between 2.5% and 5% because of this pandemic.
We talked about cholera, smallpox, the black plague, the universal flu and we could also add the yellow fever, of 1871, which hit the cities of Corrientes and Buenos Aires.
What did they all have in common?
That when we were attacked we were not warned.
We were not ready.
To top it off, in many cases it was not known where the contagion came from.
Therefore, the responses and reactions were not effective in countering evil.
What did we learn from all those fatalities?
Something very important, that the danger of the virus is enhanced with disinformation.
I explain them to you.
In the 14th century, instead of dealing with rats and lack of hygiene, it was argued that the sinful lifestyle of many had unleashed divine wrath.
In the 20th century, instead of showing the true causes of that flu, reality was distorted and the bug was out of control.
That way he spread across five continents.
Therefore, we may have learned once that we must handle ourselves with the truth.
As much as it hurts.
Another great teaching at that time was that we will have to stay on guard even after the storm passes.
Because there have always been second and third waves that have taken the unsuspecated.
But above all, we can venture wonderful times of growth.
Because after the Black Death the Renaissance emerged.
Because after the universal flu came the 1920’s, the most fruitful and avant-garde of all time.
Yes, at the end of the tunnel, the sun awaits us.
